<subSubSection id="C32642967037EB592AC9FA32671E6112" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B83111D7037EB592AC9FA32671E6112" blockId="21.[151,1436,1410,2013]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592AC9FA32641F6136" bold="true" box="[199,334,1518,1544]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for Eric F. LoPresti, ecologist and evolutionary biologist, who collected the host material from which it was reared.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32642967037EB592AC9F9EA67A66072" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B83111D7037EB592AC9F9EA679D616E" blockId="21.[151,1436,1410,2013]" box="[199,716,1590,1616]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592AC9F9EA6457616E" bold="true" box="[199,262,1590,1616]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Host.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3C6A9E7037EB592B03F9EA6495616E" box="[269,452,1590,1616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Zygophyllaceae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C6A9E7037EB592BC1F9EB679D616E" authority="Standl." box="[463,716,1590,1616]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Fagonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="laevis">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592BC1F9EB6727616E" box="[463,630,1590,1616]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fagonia laevis</emphasis>
Standl.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83111D7037EB592AC9F98667F661DE" blockId="21.[151,1436,1410,2013]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592AC9F986642F614A" bold="true" box="[199,382,1626,1652]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Larval biology.</emphasis>
Apparently a leafminer. The host material was collected to rear leaf-mining larvae of a gelechiid moth, and the presence of the flies only became evident when the puparia appeared. The rearing vial also contained fruits and stems, so the possibility of these as feeding sites cannot be entirely excluded, but as far as is known all 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C6A9E7037EB592B03F91A64F061DE" authorityName="Steyskal" authorityYear="1980" box="[269,417,1734,1760]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Haplopeodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592B03F91A64F061DE" box="[269,417,1734,1760]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Haplopeodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are leafminers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83111D7037EB592AC9F936663D603A" blockId="21.[151,1436,1410,2013]" box="[199,876,1770,1796]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592AC9F9366419603A" bold="true" box="[199,328,1770,1796]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="13070D987037EB592B59F93664F9603A" box="[343,424,1770,1796]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–39" captionStartId="45.[151,264,1811,1835]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,198,1787]" captionTargetId="figure-17@45.[151,1436,181,1787]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURES 32–39. Haplopeodes loprestii Eiseman &amp; Lonsdale, spec. nov.; 32: holotype male; 33: paratype female; 34: puparia; 35: holotype male, dorsal; 36: same, lateral; 37: same, head; 38: paratype female, dorsal; 39: same, lateral." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4545349" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4545349/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) Pale, straw-colored; formed externally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83111D7037EB592AC9F8D267A66072" blockId="21.[151,1436,1410,2013]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="B948CD0F7037EB592AC9F8D264A46016" bold="true" box="[199,501,1806,1832]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Phenology and voltinism.</emphasis>
The two known specimens were reared from larvae that fed in March, pupating by the 20 
<superScript id="7C49BC557037EB592AD2F8EE65B8607E" attach="left" box="[220,233,1842,1856]" fontSize="6" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">th</superScript>
and emerging as adults four to six weeks later.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
